{"id":14881421,"mediaExerciseId":"ff131ae3-97b0-4c7c-b369-98de9c56db68","exerciseName":"22","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612376,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":454,"solutions":[{"id":5998407,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to show the ratio of the two assets with equal risk premiums and betas. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/62d90d155dd430453251813f1c159fed/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/62d90d155dd430453251813f1c159fed/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **capital asset pricing model (CAPM)** is an equation that shows how systematic risk and expected returns are related. The CAPM informs us that the expected return is influenced by the time value of money, theÂ risk premium, and the stock's beta compared to an average value.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/5a142d28e0ce795ce6b5fc10fbd5257c/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/5a142d28e0ce795ce6b5fc10fbd5257c/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"We can see the relationship between risk and return using the capital asset pricing model (CAPM). It demonstrates that an investment's expected return is proportional to the risk-free return with a systematic risk depending on the security's beta. \n\n**The reward-to-risk ratio, which is essentially the risk premium, may be used to calculate the CAPM**. This is calculated by adjusting the reward-to-risk premium model and summing the expected return.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":254,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/072dfac4f4de253c97c745f40b961901/lateximg_large.png","width":1050},"regular":{"height":128,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/072dfac4f4de253c97c745f40b961901/lateximg.png","width":525}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"All assets must have the same risk-to-reward ratio, as per the risk-to-reward ratio. The risk-to-reward is shown as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\dfrac{\\text{R }_\\text{A}{- }{R}_{f}}{\\text{B}_\\text{A}}&=\\dfrac{\\text{R }_\\text{B}{- }{R}_{f}}{\\text{B}_\\text{B}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\nWhere: \n$$\\begin{aligned}\n{\\text{R}_{}}& = {\\text{Expected return}} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{f}}& = {\\text{Risk-free interest rate }} \\\\\n\n{\\text{B}}&= {\\text{Beta}} \n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"**When two investments are compared, the reward-to-risk ratio is calculated.**\n\nSince the numerator of each equation represents the investment's risk premium, the equation predicts that both assets will equate to one because they are the same.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":137,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/7d66c45e9c03fb1857d6f410be569040/lateximg_large.png","width":1030},"regular":{"height":69,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/1ce3bed9b87e75087f59b30ecca63066/7d66c45e9c03fb1857d6f410be569040/lateximg.png","width":516}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"76ef2620-55d9-4fca-b88e-1e24a7d059a0","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881422,"exerciseName":"23","page":454,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a4f498e8-7d3c-4bec-9aee-4d8aa7a2876a","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-questions-and-problems-23-a4f498e8-7d3c-4bec-9aee-4d8aa7a2876a"},{"id":14881423,"exerciseName":"24","page":454,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"da8b55e4-3fc9-4ca2-af44-7642637d35b5","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-questions-and-problems-24-da8b55e4-3fc9-4ca2-af44-7642637d35b5"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881420,"exerciseName":"21","page":454,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"d4c870b9-923f-4af5-afaf-77a01bd901c1","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-questions-and-problems-21-d4c870b9-923f-4af5-afaf-77a01bd901c1"},{"id":14881419,"exerciseName":"20","page":453,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"cefc6457-4524-4007-862c-8c7bb3abb30b","_webUrl":"https://quizlet